Predicticting Heart Disease in Patients

By: Grace Co

Introduction

This project will focus on predicting heart disease using a dataset from the UCI Heart Disease dataset. According to the American Heart Association, heart failure can progress, which is why researchers have identified four stages of the disease. This dataset includes information on 303 patients, each with 14 attributes, including their heart disease classification (ranging from 0, indicating no heart disease, to 4, indicating very severe heart disease). The goal is to analyze these attributes and build a model to predict whether a future undiagnosed patient has some form of heart disease.

The UCI Heart Disease dataset provides information on various health factors for each patient. These factors (represented in each column) include: age, sex, chest pain type, resting blood pressure, serum cholestoral (mg/dl), fasting blood sugar, resting electrocardiographic results, maximum heart rate achieved, presence of exercise induced angina, ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest, the slope of the peak exercise ST segment, number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flouroscopy, presence of heart defect, and severity of heart disease.

The goal is to analyze these factors (predictor variables) and identify relationships between them that might help predict the presence and severity of heart disease in future patients.

Methods

In order to determine the diagnosis of heart disease in new patients, I have chosen three factors serum cholestoral (chol), maximum heart rate achieved (thalach) and ST depression (oldpeak). As shown above, there seems to be a correlation between these three factors and their ability to determine whether or not a patient has heart disease. Therefore, these three data columns will be selected, as well as the patient's diagnosis of heart disease (num), which details the level of heart disease the patient has.

I plan to scale the data in order to accurately compare the three values, and then create a classifier using the K-nearest neighbours algorithm. As a part of this process, I will first split our combined regions dataset into a training and testing set, and then run a classification to determine which category (affected by heart disease or not), the patient is.

The data will be visualized as scatter plots in order to clearly visualize a trend between the three variables. The points will be coloured based on the individuals outcome from the dataset. The unknown patients will be plotted against the known individuals from the dataset. The analysis will compare their values with the neighbors in order to predict the diagnosis.

Expected Outcomes and Significance:

From this project, I expect to find that cholestoral, maximum heart rate and ST depression are correlated with a diagnosis of heart disease. So far from the preliminary exploratory data analysis, I predict that increased cholestoral and ST depression while slightly decreased maximum heart rate has a positive relationship with heart disease.

This data analysis is relevant in hospital settings, since it allows predictions of heart disease to be made with limited testing.

It is however important to keep in mind that heart disease has many more factors than the ones that I am studying so, by classifying new patients against this dataset, it may only indicate a possibility of heart disease, not a confirmation of heart disease. Further testing would be required. The future applications of this analysis include incorporating more data on the individuals in order to not only predict if the individual has heart disease, but also the stage and level of heart disease the patient is currently at. Additionally, in subsequent research we can use different columns of the data set to see the impact of those variables on the correlation value and whether they can help predict with more accuracy and explore more relationships between the sets of data such as answering questions like which heart disease risk factors differ most between men and women?
